### Test CORS Configuration
### This file contains HTTP requests to test CORS functionality

### 1. Test OPTIONS request (Preflight)
OPTIONS http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login HTTP/1.1
Origin: http://localhost:3000
Access-Control-Request-Method: POST
Access-Control-Request-Headers: Content-Type, Authorization

###

### 2. Test actual POST request with CORS headers
POST http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json
Origin: http://localhost:3000

{
  "username": "admin",
  "password": "123456"
}

###

### 3. Test GET request to verify CORS
GET http://localhost:5000/api/users HTTP/1.1
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN_HERE
Origin: http://localhost:3000

###

### 4. Test with different origin (should fail if not in allowed list)
POST http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json
Origin: http://localhost:9999

{
  "username": "admin",
  "password": "123456"
}

###

### 5. Test with Vite development server origin
POST http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json
Origin: http://localhost:5173

{
  "username": "admin",
  "password": "123456"
}

###

### Instructions for testing:
### 1. Start the API server: dotnet run --project StoreManagement.API
### 2. Run these requests to verify CORS is working
### 3. Check the response headers for Access-Control-Allow-Origin
### 4. For request #3, replace YOUR_JWT_TOKEN_HERE with a real token from login

### Expected CORS headers in response:
### Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://localhost:3000 (or the origin you're testing from)
### Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS
### Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type, Authorization
### Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
